          "body": "The miraculous tongues of 2:4-11 are *known human languages* (dialektos, 2:6, 8), not ecstatic utterance. The diaspora Jews from fifteen-plus regions (2:9-11) each hear Galileans speaking *the mighty deeds of God* (megaleia tou theou, 2:11) in their own native dialect. The miracle is twofold: a reversal of Babel (Genesis 11), where God scattered humanity by confusing language, now reunited around the gospel of Christ; and a sign of the universal scope of the new-covenant mission. The languages catalogued in 2:9-11 will become the geographical map of the book of Acts and the New Testament's missionary reach. Tongues at Pentecost is not private edification; it is public, intelligible proclamation of who God is and what He has done in Christ — the first sermon in fifteen languages simultaneously."
